"Yes, sir. They should be on their way by now. We gave them time to pack food from the mess hall." 05:00 whole, Exodus connected in the vehicle segment gathering. Lieutenant Shaw stood on a box, starting to speak.
"We will head to Ianos City outside 50 miles to the I-131 frontline base. We will support the ongoing siege operation, and then attack Ianos City, clearing out the rebels there. We will use this as our base, pushing into the mountain area." Lieutenant Shaw explained. "Take your squad, prepare to depart."
The squad scattered, with each platoon unit boarding a tank under the leadership of their platoon leader. Collins climbed onto a tank at the front of the convoy, sitting with Nimich, Kreis, and two new recruits. Collins remembered they had arrived a few days ago, but didn't know them well. He sat on the edge of the tank, legs dangling in the air, adjusting his backpack and radio equipment, and connecting it to his headset and throat microphone.
"Hey, Collins, did Harris still have Snowball?" Nimich asked after they settled in.
"You mean the chicken he stole?" Collins thought back to the scene that morning when they stole chickens from the farm. "That's right, I'm sure of it."
Collins glanced at another tank, seeing Harris and his squad members. He could vaguely see a small chicken peeking out from the back of Harris's backpack.
"Yes, he still has that chicken," Collins replied, just as the tank commander's hatch opened with a loud clang, and the commander appeared before them.
"All tanks have departed," the commander calmly and clearly said into his radio, as the tanks and armored cars of the armored platoon rumbled to life, and began to move forward. Collins's Chronos tank relaxed its brakes, moving forward, and joining the convoy. The tanks formed a wedge formation as they crossed the Itanian plains. The winter storm had frozen the wetlands and forest, but the mud remained.
About an hour later, a new recruit (Collins remembered his name was Osborn) spoke up, "Lieutenant, you've been on the front lines since the start of the war, right?"
"Yes, since the Firestorm operation," Collins replied. "We thought we'd be done in a few weeks, but... we underestimated them."
"Not just underestimated."  Nimich joined in the conversation. "Their weapons and troops exceeded our expectations. They shot down the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks, and another one, the Erebus, last month. Damn it, we should be able to see it on the road."
"Okay, I'll bravely fight for the federation." Osborn said resolutely, "I won't be intimidated by those terrorists."
"You're saying that now, but from what I see, most of us young recruits like you will pee our pants as soon as we hear gunfire." Kreis said.
"We'll see." Collins chuckled. Osborn remained silent.
"Exodus deputy commander! Exodus commander!" Collins' radio device called out. "We've detected a heat signature 20 degrees to the right and 350 yards ahead."
Collins climbed onto the tank, put on his optical visor. After switching to thermal imaging mode, he saw the heat signature in the distance.
"Yes, I see them," Collins said into his throat microphone.
"Are they the enemy?" another new recruit, Natalia, asked.
"Can't tell," Collins replied, opening his microphone. "Exodus platoon, unless under attack, don't fire, let's get them out."
As they got closer, the faint heat signal went from a vague spot to a clearer outline. One of them ran to a place, picked up something, then ran back to the small hill. They then lay down, entering a shooting position.
"We've encountered the enemy!" when the orange tracer shot out from the ridge, Lieutenant Shaw called out over the radio. The bullets hit the side of the tank with a series of loud clanks, and the squad members jumped down from the tank, taking cover behind it. A anti-tank missile screamed over, hitting the ground behind the tank formation and exploding, sending shrapnel into one of the tanks. Another missile hit the side of a Stryker armored personnel carrier (APS-Cerberus) and exploded. After the ammunition detonated, the crew members of the armored personnel carrier crawled out, looking for cover.
"Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees to the right, 300 yards. Open fire!" the tank commander called out over the radio. The main guns of Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, and the shells screamed towards the ridge, exploding and sending mud and debris flying into the air.
"Send out the sentry robot!" Knox shouted, still observing the ridge with his binoculars. The rear hatch of a "Hellhound" opened, and a soldier without a weapon stepped out, wearing a custom-made headset. He shouted orders into the square microphone, and two "Sentry" robots responded by emerging. Their long, thin metal arms and legs moved forward, and they ran quickly. The robots were equipped with weapons, but they were all hung on their backs.
"Kill or capture?" Kreis asked, observing and wondering.
"Looks like they're going to capture alive," Collins guessed, seeing the two Sentry robots disappear into the smokes and ashes. The shouting and gunfire from the ridge gradually stopped. After a while, the two Sentry robots came back, dragging a person, leaving behind a trail of footprints in the mud and snow. Upon reaching the safe area, the robots threw the captive to the ground, and he fell heavily onto the mud and snow, groaning in pain.
He struggled to stand up, Lieutenant Shaw walked over. Lieutenant Shaw turned to one of the sentry robots. “How many?”
“Three are dead, sir,” the sentry robot replied. “The rest have fled on foot.”
Shaw nodded, turned to Collins and Kreis standing nearby. “Can you two take this person away?”
